<br>
When I was just a young leaf, I remember going to several places to try to fight assorted critters, only to find that many places which would yield decent experience and the occasional nice piece of gear which I could render for some money, to be camped and farmed by very high level types who were cleaning out the critters before I could get a shot at them.  Made me very mad, because I could have really used the experience, and the money would have helped replace that leather and banded I was wearing.<br>
<br>
Rathe comes to mind, in particular.  As well as a couple of dozen other places.  It still makes me sick to run through that zone on my way to other places, and see the legion of 50+ people there farming platinum.  Get a job, for the love of mud!<br>
<br>
So I decided that, when I became one of those 50+ seasoned people, I would not farm Rathe, or any other place that so many people farm so they can &quot;kiloplat&quot; and &quot;uber&quot; themselves.  And I don't.  It's easy - just say &quot;No&quot;, and leave those areas to the people who can get a challege from the fight.<br>
<br>
So if Khub is not farming for platinum so he can &quot;uber&quot; his gear, like so many of you have suggested he do, then that puts him a couple of hundred points up on the rest of you farmers out there, just my feelings on the subject of &quot;farming&quot;.  If he's earning his armor the old fashioned way, then more power to him.  I have a lot more respect for someone who earned their gear, rather than farmed platinum for it.  If you're farming for platinum, then why not just do lowbies a favor and go buy it?  At least you won't be stealing mobs from those who could really use the experience.  I consider farming and buying platinum to be about the same - neither one are much of an effort.<br>
<br>
<br>
I happen to know Khublaikhan.  He is a very well respected Warrior, and every hunt I have ever been on with him has brought me back alive, and well funded.  One of the biggest things I've learned from him is aggro management - I can do a lot of damage, but if I gain the ire of the critter we're trying to kill, then the cleric/druid now has TWO people to heal, instead of one.  This is counterproductive.  So now, I wait to engage, and if I appear to start to draw aggro, I back my elven hiney off and let main tank regain it.  Pretty simple, if you ask me.  It also keeps me from picking up so many bruises...<br>
<br>
The only problems I've ever seen from hunting in pickup groups is that some people don't know their roles.  If you have a main tank that cannot keep aggro because you're stepping up and hitting with your &quot;uber&quot; weapon, then fine - YOU tank.  And ask him to back off.  I'm sure he'd be happy to let someone else tank, take the damage, and get killed, if they want to be stubborn about it.  If your main tank can't keep aggro, it's not because he's not doing his job - it's because YOU are not doing yours.<br>
<br>
I also know that Khublaikhan has endless patience, simply because he's hunted with me a few times, and you would not BELIEVE how much that can tax someone's patience.  My puns alone will run most people off a cliff...<br>
<br>
You may not want to hunt with Khublaikhan, and that's fine.  I'll hunt with him anytime, anywhere.  I've done so many times, and never died in one of his groups.  I also come back a much more experienced Ranger.  If you want to be a tanking cleric, fine - state that up front.  But don't start trashing someone because you, as a cleric, can hit harder than they can.<br>
<br>
Oh, and as to his name?  Yes, I'm <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">certain</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> it's not as august or fecund as &quot;Squishytoes&quot;, but it is a decent name, at least...<br>
<br>
