<br>
That said, I'd like to take this opportunity to point out something..<br>
<br>
In this example the cleric decided that the tank was a suck tank on the basis of his gear, and the fact that the cleric got agro from melee.<br>
<br>
Now, whether he's a suck tank, or she's(he's) a suck cleric, I care not, for this discussion. <br>
<br>
First, (and I'm now making this a generalized discussion, so keep up) that farging hammer..can anyone supply numbers on how much aggro that proc generates?( I mean numbers. &quot;A shitload&quot; or &quot;Not much&quot; isn't what I want here*grin*)<br>
<br>
Ok, next to get into the ways a warrior has at his disposal to generate aggo.<br>
<br>
We have this cute little button, that says &quot;taunt&quot; on it.<br>
<br>
No, really, that's it.<br>
<br>
That's at a warrior's disposal, regardless of his level or his gear(I'll get to other factors in a moment).<br>
<br>
What does that button do? Sometimes, nothing. Most times, though, it puts that warrior at x+1, x being the highest batch of aggro generated by a group member at that moment.(and if my descriptions are off, please, someone with the appropriate numbers, correct me)<br>
<br>
Like, say the slower slows the mob, and generates 200 aggro points(I'm tossing out a random number, I have no idea on the actual points, just how the general system works), a successful taunt will give the warrior 201 aggro points, thus the highest aggo in the group at the moment. <br>
<br>
The cleric comes along with that godsbedamned hammer(I don't have issues, really*grin*), and gets it to proc three times in a row(just a hypothetical number here, relax, clerics), for let's say 100 aggro points each(It may be more or less aggro than a slow, I don't know), putting the cleric at 300 aggro, 99 more than the warrior. <br>
<br>
Yes, a successful taunt will get aggro back, provided you're not going to continue to proc(I've seen Kerridwynn spam my screen with procs, it seems to me that that hammer procs awfully easy, just an observation, though).<br>
<br>
But you see where I'm going with this.<br>
<br>
Yes, a warrior can get weapons that increase his/her hate exponentially.  With Sar, I really neglected my armor/hitpoints to spend cash on really great weapons, because trying to maintain aggro from SK's and dumb ol' rogues 10 levels higher than me*grin* got tiresome.<br>
<br>
But if a warrior doesn't have great taunt weapons(either because they don't know how important they are, or because they flat can't afford them), then you, as groupmates need to understand that, and if you're grouping with them, compensate for it, or at least give them a minute to get their job done, before you start raising hell about skill.<br>
<br>
I know the general disdain for pickup groups. I hate them, because my guild is full of hellishly skilled individuals. So, even really good mechanical players seem kinda subpar to me, because of the level of competence I've grown used to, so, that part, I *do* understand.<br>
<br>
But I get tired of hearing people griping about how the warrior let someone get aggro.  Warriors can't help it, sometimes.<br>
They can almost always get it right back, but aggro control is as much up to the warrior's groupmates as it is up to him.<br>
<br>
Now, to warriors...some advice.<br>
<br>
Disarm seemed to work as a taunt, and I have heard that begging does as well. Get fast weapons with stun or other nasty procs, search the bazaar, there are great weapons in all sorts of price ranges.<br>
<br>
~Trae, former warrior, still a bit disgruntled about the bad rap they get sometimes. <p><center> 
